    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="act-8a-1-2-task-1">
      <statement>
					<p>
						Next, recall that we want <m>f</m> and <m>T_3</m> to share the same function and derivative values at <m>a = 0</m> up to and including the third derivative.  For instance, one of the four needed equations is <m>T_3'(0) = f'(0)</m>.  Use the four equations your work in the preceding question to determine the values of <m>c_0</m>, <m>c_1</m>, <m>c_2</m>, and <m>c_3</m>.

					</p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer>
        <p><m>c_0 = 1</m>; <m>c_1 = 1</m>; <m>c_2 = \frac{1}{2}</m>; <m>c_3 = \frac{1}{6}</m>.
					</p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
						Since <m>T_3(0) = f(0)</m>, this means <m>c_0 = 1</m>.  Next, <m>T_3'(0) = f'(0)</m> tells us that <m>c_1 = 1</m>.  Using <m>T_3''(0) = f''(0)</m>, <m>2c_2 = 1</m> so that <m>c_2 = \frac{1}{2}</m>.  And finally, the last condition is <m>T_3'''(0) = f'''(0)</m>, which implies that <m>6c_3 = 1</m>, so <m>c_3 = \frac{1}{6}</m>.
					</p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="act-8a-1-2-task-2">
      <statement>
					<p>
						Having now determined the numerical values of <m>c_0</m>, <m>c_1</m>, <m>c_2</m>, and <m>c_3</m>, use appropriate computational technology to plot the function <m>T_3(x) = c_0 + c_1 x + c_2 x^2 + c_3 x^3</m> along with <m>f(x)=e^x</m>, <m>T_1(x)=1+x</m>, and <m>T_2(x) = 1 + x + \frac{1}{2}x^2</m> in the same window as shown in <xref ref="F-8a-1-act-2">Figure</xref>.  
          </p>

						<figure xml:id="F-8a-1-act-2">
							<caption>The function <m>f(x)=e^x</m>, its tangent line <m>T_1(x)=1+x</m>, and the quadratic approximation <m>T_2(x) = 1 + x + \frac{1}{2}x^2</m> near the point <m>(0,f(0))</m>.</caption>
							<image width="50%" source="images/8a_1_act_2" />
						</figure>

          <p>  
						What do you notice?  For approximately which values of <m>x</m> is <m>|f(x)-T_3(x)| \lt 0.1</m>?
					</p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>T_3(x)</m> appears to be an even better approximation than <m>T_2(x)</m> near <m>a = 0</m> and that the quality of the approximation extends further; <m>|f(x)-T_3(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for approximately <m>-1.3 \lt x \lt 1.1</m>.  
				</p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
						We notice that <m>T_3(x)</m> appears to be an even better approximation than <m>T_2(x)</m> near <m>a = 0</m> and that the quality of the approximation extends further.  
        </p>    
						
        <figure xml:id="F-8a-1-act-2-soln">
          <caption>The function <m>f(x)=e^x</m>, its tangent line <m>T_1(x)=1+x</m>, the quadratic approximation <m>T_2(x) = 1 + x + \frac{1}{2}x^2</m>, and the cubic approximation <m>T_3(x)</m> near the point <m>(0,f(0))</m>.</caption>
          <image width="50%" source="images/8a_1_act_2_soln"/>
        </figure>
				<p>
          We can see the better approximation by <m>T_3(x)</m> in the figure, and if we do some computations, we can see that for certain <m>x</m> near <m>a = 0</m>, <m>T_3(x)</m> is closer to <m>e^x</m> than <m>T_2(x)</m> and that the set of <m>x</m>-values for which <m>|f(x)-T_3(x)| \lt 0.1</m> is wider than for which <m>|f(x)-T_2(x)| \lt 0.1</m>.  We found in <xref ref="act-8a-1-1">Activity</xref> that <m>|f(x)-T_2(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for approximately <m>-0.9 \lt x \lt 0.8</m>; here, <m>|f(x)-T_2(x)| \lt 0.1</m> for approximately <m>-1.3 \lt x \lt 1.1</m>.  
				</p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task workspace="3cm" xml:id="act-8a-1-2-task-3">
      <statement>
					<p>
						What if we wanted a degree-<m>4</m> polynomial approximation to <m>f(x) = e^x</m> near <m>a = 0</m>?  Based on the patterns you've observed in <m>T_1</m>, <m>T_2</m>, and <m>T_3</m>, conjecture values for the constants <m>d_0, \ldots, d_4</m> for a function <m>T_4</m> of the form
						<me>T_4(x) = d_0 + d_1 x + d_2 x^2 + d_3 x^3 + d_4 x^4</me>
						that satisfies <m>T_4(0) = f(0)</m>, <m>T_4'(0) = f'(0)</m>, <m>\ldots</m>, <m>T_4^{(4)}(0) = f^{(4)}(0)</m>.  Add this function <m>T_4</m> to your plot in part (c) that includes <m>f(x)</m> and the lower-degree polynomial approximations.  What do you notice?
					</p>
      </statement>
      <hint/>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>T_4(x) = 1 + x + \frac{1}{2}x^2 + \frac{1}{6} x^3 + \frac{1}{24}x^4</m>; <m>T_4(x)</m> is an even better approximation to <m>f(x) = e^x</m> and on a still wider interval.
				</p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>T_4(x)</m> involves the term <m>d_4 x^4</m>.  When we differentiate this function <m>4</m> times, we get <m>4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1 d_4</m>.  Since <m>f^{(4)}(x) = e^x</m>, <m>f^{(4)}(0) = 1</m>, so <m>4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1 d_4 = 1</m> and therefore <m>d_4 = \frac{1}{24}</m>.  This means that 
						<me>T_4(x) = 1 + x + \frac{1}{2}x^2 + \frac{1}{6} x^3 + \frac{1}{24}x^4</me>.
					Plotting <m>T_4(x)</m> along with the earlier approximations we see that <m>T_4(x)</m> is an even better approximation to <m>f(x) = e^x</m> and on a still wider interval.
					</p>
      </solution>
    </task>
